 project advice and more.\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/section\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cp\u003e‘Spring-loaded fence clips solve a common problem without the hassle,\u0026#39; says Thomas Oldham, Co-Founder at \u003ca data-analytics-id=\"inline-link\" href=\"https://ukconstructionblog.co.uk/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\" data-url=\"https://ukconstructionblog.co.uk/\" referrerpolicy=\"no-referrer-when-downgrade\" data-hl-processed=\"none\"\u003eUK Construction Blog\u003c/a\u003e. \u0026#39;They slide directly into the gap between the fence panel and post, gripping on their own with no need for tools or drilling. The spring mechanism keeps steady pressure on the panel, holding it firmly in place even on windy days,’\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e‘They’re a practical option when panels are still solid but have started to move around. Because the clips flex as the wood shifts with temperature and moisture, they stay effective over time. Push them into position by hand, and they’ll hold without altering the fence itself.’\u003c/p\u003e\u003cfigure data-bordeaux-image-check=\"\"\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource type=\"image/webp\" srcset=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1920-80.png.webp 1920w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1600-80.png.webp 1600w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1280-80.png.webp 1280w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1024-80.png.webp 1024w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-768-80.png.webp 768w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-415-80.png.webp 415w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-360-80.png.webp 360w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-320-80.png.webp 320w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 710px) 670px, calc(100vw - 30px)\"/\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c.png\" alt=\"Brown garden fence with lush green planys and a modern wood patio seating area.\" srcset=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1920-80.png 1920w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1600-80.png 1600w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1280-80.png 1280w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-1024-80.png 1024w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-768-80.png 768w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-415-80.png 415w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-360-80.png 360w, https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c-320-80.png 320w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 710px) 670px, calc(100vw - 30px)\" loading=\"lazy\" data-original-mos=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c.png\" data-pin-media=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/9JPtLNdDse26wmQE5rQ25c.png\"/\u003e\u003c/picture\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003cp\u003e(Image credit: Future PLC/ Claire Lloyd Davies)\u003c/p\u003e\u003c/figure\u003e\u003cp\u003eAs well as fence clips, you can also invest in fence wedges or foam which have a similar effect.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e‘To know where to place your fence wedges, start by identifying the panels that rattle the most by gently shaking the fence. Typically, three to four wedges at different points of the post will work best to prevent movement and rattling,’ advises Mark.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e‘Then use your hand to gently push the wedges as far as possible into the gap, and then use a hammer to secure them further in place. The wedges should fit tightly between the panels and the post.\u0026#39;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u0026#39;Fence panel wedges are an ideal method for preventing rattling as they’re easy to install, long-lasting and can easily be removed if you need to \u003ca data-analytics-id=\"inline-link\" href=\"https://www.idealhome.co.uk/decor\" data-auto-tag-linker=\"true\" data-before-rewrite-redirect=\"https://w